Hans,

There may be ways to do what you want.  I&#39;d like to be sure I know
what that is, though.  It sounds like you&#39;d like to use JUnit 4 to run
JUnit 3 tests, but having the @Ignore annotation observed.  Is this
true?  Are there other features you&#39;d like to be able to use?  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 1/23/07, hans_schwaebli &lt;hans_schwaebli@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Our old JUnit tests are written for JUnit 3.8.1.
&gt;
&gt; They first extended TestCase. After we introduced JMock, all our
&gt; TestCases extend MockObjectTestCase.
&gt;
&gt; This is because we extend from our own JUnit test helper class which
&gt; extends from MockObjectTestCase.
&gt;
&gt; Now we use the .jar file from JUnit 4.2 and JMock 1.1.
&gt;
&gt; But only if we write new tests, which don&#39;t extend MockObjectTestCase
&gt; and TestCase and insert the method below for Eclipse 3.1.2, the tests
&gt; are run as JUnit 4 tests. Otherwise they are run as JUnit 3 tests.
&gt;
&gt;   public static junit.framework.Test suite()
&gt;   {
&gt;       return new JUnit4TestAdapter(MyTest.class);
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt; It would be much work to refactor our old test. I thought it would be
&gt; easy to use the new JUnit 4 features on them like @Ignore.
&gt;
&gt; Why are our tests always run as JUnit 3 tests if they extend from
&gt; TestCase? Does anyone has a solution for us for using the new JUnit 4
&gt; features without refactoring our tests very much?
